{
  "texts": [
    "While there is ongoing research work on improving reasoning in large language models (Huang and Chen-Chuan 2022; Wei et al. 2022; Zhao et al. 2022; Wang et al. 2023; Long 2023; Weng et al. 2023; Lu et al. 2023; Taylor 2023; Zhang et al. 2023; Besta et al. 2023), there is still a degree of skepticism on these nascent capabilities (Xu et al. 2023; Huang et al. 2023) and additional challenges that remain to be overcome (Ji et al. 2023; Shi et al. 2023).",
    "Importantly, a culture gap has been identified in the understanding capabilities of existing models (Liu et al. 2023).",
    "Recent advances in understanding and mitigating social biases in language models (Zmigrod et al. 2019; Huang et al. 2019b; Li et al. 2020; Liang et al. 2021; Ousidhoum et al. 2021; Nozza et al. 2021), and computer vision systems (Joo et al. 2020; Wang et al. 2020a), coupled with a development of benchmarks (Nangia et al. 2020; Nadeem et al. 2020) for identification of malignant stereotypes in AI models, may pave the way towards quantifying the extent of xenophobic bias and harm in large pre-trained AI systems.",
    "Yet, for contemporary base models, the solution likely needs to be multi-faceted and case-specific.",
    "Multi-lingual (Huang et al. 2019; Xu et al. 2021; Srinivasan et al. 2021) models may help incorporate a wider variety of viewpoints, especially if grounded in geospatially diverse imagery aimed at improving representation-though there are still open challenges when it comes to ensuring equal performance (Wang et al. 2021a; Monojit and Amit 2021; Ramesh et al. 2023)."
  ]
}